stylometry: There are several different types of costs that affect the managing of products in inventory.  Order cost (set-up), holding costs, production costs, delivery costs, and damage or soilage costs are all costs that play a role.  Order costs usually include a fixed cost with each order placed plus a fee per unit ordered.  For example, if I order 300 t-shirts and there is a fixed order cost of $100 and a unit cost of $1 per shirt then the total order cost will be $400. Holding costs are costs such as rent, shelving space, storage, etc. for the product inventory and can be either a variable cost or fixed cost depending on the rate. Management wants to push inventory quickly in order to keep holding costs down as much as possible. Production costs are how much it costs to make the product, market the product, pay for equipment, or pay employees.  Delivery costs may be added on to an order and there may be a fixed amount each time or it can be based on the size of the order.  Soilage or damage costs are costs that occur when inventory is soilable such as food that isn't sold before expiration or products damaged in production, delivery, etc. and this is a variable cost. Total Cost=Fixed Cost+(Variable Cost*Unit)
